**Mandatory handins**  Two Mandatory handins

[Mandatory 1](#bookmark=id.wuu175xjrg4k)   
[Mandatory 2 (eksamensprojekt)](#bookmark=id.hav7rkn4bxu1)

You have to hand in the **2 mandatories**  in order to be allowed to attend any Mobile exam. The mandatories need to be approved by the teacher.   
Failure to comply, will prevent you from attending the exam (and any re-exam) and result in you losing one exam attempt.  
For the exam it is a required, that you can explain each line of your own code.

Technical deadline to hand in the mandatories is **24 hours before your exam**.

**Exam project:** For the exam, you will develop an app, which demonstrates your skills and understanding of the course curriculum. There will be no written report.   
See [guideline](https://docs.google.com/document/d/1Yp01Bar7fvFP6vU9jRMDyuFup_34l639qAiIhrzCEbE/edit) for the exam project and the exam.  
You are allowed to work in groups, in order to make somthing bigger or more complex. 

**Exam: May 30, June 2,3,4**

At the exam, you are invited to present your exam-app. This includes app-demo, explaining the app-concept and arguing for your choice of technologies.   
You are welcome to prepare a slideshow, but this is not mandatory.  
Each student gets 30 minutes in total. Of this, 5 minutes is for practical setup and giving grade. This leaves max 25 minutes for examination.   
The student-presentation itself can be max 10 minutes. The remaining 10-15 minutes are for questions about the the curriculum in general and the exam-project.

**CONTENT AND LEARNING OUTCOMES**

In this course you will learn how to build native apps for Android and iOS.

The goal is to learn how to design and implement mobile applications (apps) for  
phone/tablet. You will learn how to create prototype apps, based on customer requirements.  
During classes we will build apps, that demonstrate the features mentioned below.  
We will cover best-practices, used in mobile development. Students will be able to run their app on  
both software simulator, and on physical devices: phone and tablet.  
Today it is possible to develop mobile apps, which can solve many of today’s user requirements. Using built-in sensors, such as GPS, Accelerometer, Gyroscope, Pedometer, Altitude,  
Microphone, Camera and Magnetometer developers can build apps which are far more  
functionality than desktop applications. Add in the connection to Cloud services, such as Database, Authentication and Artificial Intelligence(AI), the mobile app has access to all the services a desktop application has.

**Requirements**:  
You need a **fast computer** with min. 8GB ram and Solid State Disk (SSD). The reason for this is, that Android Studio, Xcode and the simulators use a lot of CPU time. 

**Tools**:  
Android Studio [https://developer.android.com/studio](https://developer.android.com/studio)  
Xcode [https://developer.apple.com/develop/](https://developer.apple.com/develop/)

**Mobile application topics:**

* Mobile Applicataion User Interface  
* Mobile Application Architecture  
* App Lifecycle  
* Design Pattern  
* Responsive Design

**Mobile application features:**

* Multitouch Gesture  
* Pop up view  
* Map  
* Camera  
* Sensors  
* List  
* Cloud Database  
* Cloud Authentication

**Knowledge**  
The student will gain necessary knowledge to build a prototype mobile app, based on user  
requirements. This includes knowing the necessary development tools, cloud-services and programming languages.

**Skills**    
The student will learn how to work with the IDEs Android studio and Xcode to build native mobile applications. The student will learn to combine previous knowledge in order to solve problems. Also the skill to find relevant information on the internet will be trained.

**Competence**  
The student will learn how to convert user-requirements to a mobile application. Learn the different steps in mobile develoment, from talks with the client, prototyping and integrating with cloud services. The student will gain competence in building well-organized apps, using extendable and reusable code base.

**Mandatory exercises**  
There will be a number of mandatory projects, which MUST be handed in before the student can attend any of the 3 exam-attempts.

**Teaching format:**  
Class presentations of new material. In-class exercises. Group work and individual assignments.

**Exam project:**  
The exam project is not mandatory. But it is highly recommended, that the student builds an app to present at the exam. This will make it much more likely for the student to have a great exam.

**Exam**

* Oral 23 minute exam with internal censor  
* Student presents exam project:   
  * App demo  
  * Explain interesting part of code and choice of technologies   
  * Q & A about project and curriculum  
* No report
